title: For Sale/Trade:  Marlin .32 Special Model 336 SC
postcontent: Excellent condition 1949 Marlin model 336, 32 Special with Ballard type rifling  NOT MICRO GROOVE!  Only flaw on gun is a few small nicks along left side of barrel and magazine tube with faint patina (browning of blueing)--not rust.  I found out from previous owner this was done by one of those clamp-on sling swivel mounts often used on these type rifles.  This gun is exceptional looking otherwise and is enviably accurate.  Beautiful black walnut original stock has perch belly forend and has only the most minor marks (2-3) on the entire stockworks.  Also have one full box of Win. 170 grain bullet ammo from the late 80s mint, and 50 fresh reloads from never yet fired virgin Win. brass with Speer 170 bullets, and 16 sized, primed twice fired, ready to load Win. cases.  Those are the 16 cases I used to test load and find a super accurate one.  This rifle has a clean and shiny apparently pristine bore and is a rarity.  It is in impressive cosmetic condition, and is as accurate or more so than any Marlin out there.  Ballard rifling was simply the best in these guns.  Will also sell like new Lyman dies for the rifle and the ammo supplies mentioned.  Also mounted on see-thru mounts is a mint Leupold 2-7x33mm VariX-I scope that includes original box, cards, etc.  $675 for gun Wide-View scope mounts and scope.   This is an awesome setup.  Reason for parting?  I'm reduced to small game hunting due to arthritis issues.

title: For Sale/Trade:  AR-15 "ghost" gun lower 80% w/ jig
postcontent:
**For sale in person SUNDAY ONLY between Milwaukee and Appleton**

I have a few 80% polymer lowers (reinforced around the critical areas, such as the buffer tube) with the jigs (guides that clamp on over the lower to show you exactly where to drill your holes) and screws needed. These are the G150 model (2nd gen) and normally run $100 plus shipping. They do not include any drill bits (I can include one new set of the drill bits and mill bit for an extra $30).

These are perfectly legal to transform at home into an AR-15 rifle or pistol lower without needing to get the manufacturing stamp from the ATF. No serial numbers, which is why they're sometimes called "ghost" guns because there's no way to track them. It only requires a drill or Dremel (drill press is easiest, or you can use a mill), and being polymer it's a lot faster and easier to drill and hollow out the requisite spaces than aluminum to make a lightweight gun to add to your collection. All you have to do is drill/cut out the red part in the fire control pocket and drill the holes as indicated on the jig and you'll have a stripped lower for your project.

I can send one Priority Mail for $6 more.

title: For Sale:  SilencerCo Sparrow 22 Suppressor
postcontent:
The Sparrow 22 is the first silencer in the world to offer the patented multi part containment (MPC) technology, which allows the Sparrow 22 to be easily disassembled for cleaning and maintenance after heavy use.

Because the .22 LR round is not copper jacketed, molten lead and carbon debris will explode into the silencer when the projectile exits the muzzle. After some time, it is possible for a .22 suppressor to fill completely with lead and become heavy and ineffective. To avoid this issue, .22 silencers must be disassembled for cleaning and regular maintenance.

Until Silencerco introduced the Sparrow 22, the only .22 silencers that could be disassembled for cleaning required a cleaning every 50 to 200 rounds. However, often the components of those silencers would be fused together and unable to come apart. Competitor products on the market have baffles in their .22 silencers that must be removed by twisting the outer tube around the baffles and/or sliding the outer tube off of the baffles. When the lead and carbon debris adhere to the inner wall of the outer tube and fill the spaces between the baffles and the outer tube, there is simply too much buildup of fouling and lead to remove the outer tube in that manner.

title: For Sale:  Winchester Model 70 Deluxe Featherweight with Leupold Vari X 2 3X9X40 in 270 Winchester
postcontent: Like new Model 70 Featherweight Deluxe with flawless Leupold VX II scope, rings and bases. Beautiful wood, floated barrel, trigger tuned and set to 4 pounds, and as good a shooter as you'll ever find. Bought the gun while my Uncle was alive and had his gun shop. It was a present for myself after a long deployment at sea. Bought some cheap Super X ammo to break in the barrel and cleaned after each shot for the first 10 then shot 3. The first 2 touched and the third was about a 1/4 away from the first 2 at 100 yards. Cleaned the barrel again and fired 3 more. Same results but the group actually tightened up a bit. Zeroed the scope with 2 more shots that both touched and haven't fired it since. Hunted 2 or 3 times that year with it then it found a home in the back of a safe where it has been since that season ended after a thorough cleaning. My 2011 Blue Book of Gun Values shows the value at 900$ back in 2011, page 2156. I paid right around 800$ a couple years before that ( I got it at dealers cost). The scope ran about 250$ with the Leupold bases and rings around 50$. Probably shoots premium ammo even better than the Super X but I never fooled with it because a 3/4" gun with off the shelf ammo is about as good as it will ever get, regardless of all the BS you read and hear about. Fact is, I'm just a little too old to hunt as much as I used to, a litte too busy to hunt as much as I want, and collected way too many guns over the years and I'm just reducing the entire inventory to one safe. I'll keep a couple favorites but I'm letting the rest go. Fact is, the gun looks new, the scope is flawless with a lifetime guarantee, the wood is beautiful, the bluing is deep and rich as a deluxe model should be but I just don't need it. Life is too short to hunt with an ugly gun. Hunt with a beautiful American crafted work of art today and leave your son, daughter, or grandchildren with an heirloom they will be proud to own and show, whether they hunt or not. It is doubtful that you will ever again find a gun of this quality, for this price, that functions this well. And I have never, ever, seen a Winchester gun go down in value and Model 70's will be collectors items from now until we are both long gone from here. The price is firm for obvious reasons and I can't hold it. First 900$ cash takes home a gun you'll love forever.
